      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI < 5% for all QoI using Richardson extrapolation across three mesh densities.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study performed with coarse (0.8 mm), medium (0.5 mm), and fine (0.3 mm) element sizes at critical screw-rod interface. Richardson extrapolation yields GCI < 2% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. Production mesh uses medium density."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson convergence residuals below 1e-4 for all load steps; no spurious energy generation detected.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver convergence monitored across all 11 simulation cases. Force and displacement residuals converge below 1e-5 tolerance. Energy balance checks confirm no artificial energy generation. Iterative solver (PCG) accuracy verified against direct solver on representative case."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented modeling protocol with peer review and independent model reconstruction check.",
      "rationale": "A written modeling protocol specifies boundary conditions, contact definitions, material assignments, and load application procedures. An independent analyst reconstructed the model from the protocol and obtained results within 1% of the primary model, confirming low use-error risk."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with elastic-plastic titanium alloy material model and frictional contact at screw-rod interface adequately represents F1717 compression-bending physics.",
      "rationale": "The model employs a continuum FEA formulation with bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V components and frictional Coulomb contact (mu=0.2) at the screw-rod interface. Literature review and prior validation studies confirm this model form captures the dominant load-transfer mechanisms in F1717 compression-bending within the displacement range of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for each production lot; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (2.2 GPa) derived from certified material test reports for the production lot used in bench testing. Screw and rod geometry inputs obtained from coordinate measuring machine (CMM) data on representative specimens, with dimensional tolerances propagated as input uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from production lot with documented traceability; tested across two independent laboratories.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs from a single production lot were tested. Six constructs tested at FDA laboratory and five at the sponsor laboratory. Full traceability documentation (lot number, assembly records, calibration certificates) available for all specimens. Sample size exceeds minimum recommended for statistical comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two displacement rates and two construct configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single ASTM F1717 protocol at one displacement rate (5 mm/min) and one construct configuration (two-level L4-L5 surrogate). While this fully satisfies the F1717 standard, it represents a single test condition and does not span the range of clinical loading variability. Factor achieves Gradation 2; required level is 3. This gap is acknowledged and accepted given the regulatory precedent for single-condition F1717 validation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA boundary conditions and material inputs demonstrably equivalent to physical test setup; discrepancies quantified and within uncertainty bounds.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions replicate the F1717 test fixture constraints as confirmed by comparison of fixture compliance measurements with model predictions. Material inputs matched to certified test reports. Remaining discrepancies between FEA and test inputs (fixture stiffness, grip compliance) quantified and incorporated into validation uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric with acceptance threshold of 1.96; all QoI within 10% relative difference.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed for construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement. E/uval values: stiffness 0.84, yield force 1.12, force at 40 mm 1.31 — all below 1.96 threshold. Relative differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 5.7%, force at 40 mm 4.9% — all within 10% acceptance bound. Comparison satisfies Gradation 3 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI directly map to clinical performance endpoints and regulatory submission requirements for spinal implant constructs.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoI mandated by ASTM F1717 and directly relevant to the regulatory decision. Stiffness relates to load-sharing with the spine; yield force and force at 40 mm characterize fatigue and failure risk. QoI relevance to the COU is direct and well-established in the spinal implant literature."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on the same device design, material, and test protocol as the COU; no extrapolation beyond validated domain.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities use the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design, Ti-6Al-4V material, and ASTM F1717 test protocol as the COU. The FEA model is applied within the validated domain (static compression-bending, F1717 geometry, production-lot material properties). No extrapolation to untested loading modes or device variants is claimed."
    }
